{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f8a53e60-312e-4aae-8ad8-d2a352e755c4","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple's built-in crash reports**:\n\n1. **Crash reports** are saved automatically by macOS at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for files named `<YourApp>_<date>.crash` or `.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them visually.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. For richer .NET diagnostics, set the environment variable:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_EnableCrashReport=1\n   ```\n   This makes the NativeAOT runtime write a managed crash info file alongside the crash.\n\n**Start with `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — that's where you'll almost certainly find the report without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"56799345-25d4-4876-a94b-68797a9ca7b4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":321,"requestId":"1B89:3B8967:15CD11B:187F21A:6A0286DD"},"id":"230e537a-2ab5-4ba3-b1ec-5eb8db2c4f27","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:48:29.044Z","parentId":"1c9a05fc-f0ab-46f3-b516-0a8142873a6d"}
